          "comments": [
            {
              "originalPosition": 36,
              "body": "The DA token CDDL shows how to use the SPDM attestation.  Just like code, I thought it would be best to introduce small parts, i.e the spdm-claims, and then use it in an example.  I am not strongly opinionated on this. ",
              "createdAt": "2025-05-26T17:51:43Z",
              "updatedAt": "2025-05-26T17:51:43Z"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "id": "PRR_kwDOOtRXe86rAR_r",
          "commit": {
            "abbreviatedOid": "d70715c"
          },
          "author": "thomas-fossati",
          "authorAssociation": "OWNER",
          "state": "COMMENTED",
          "body": "",
          "createdAt": "2025-05-26T18:13:52Z",
          "updatedAt": "2025-05-26T18:13:52Z",
          "comments": [
            {
              "originalPosition": 36,
              "body": "I am not opinionated on how the assembly should look in the end.  However, I quite strongly believe we need to provide an outline of that.\r\nI see two core topics at work in this spec:\r\n1. How to expose SPDM in a user-friendly way;\r\n2. How to use the EAT framework to express attesters' composition in a confidential computing platform that implements some form of device assignment.\r\n\r\nThe former is 100% bottom-up; the latter needs continuous zooming in and out to ensure it all fits together.",
              "createdAt": "2025-05-26T18:13:52Z",
              "updatedAt": "2025-05-26T18:14:35Z"
            }
          ]
        }
      ]
    },
    {
